[
    {
        "content": "<p>Say I have a term like <code>a ∪ b ∪ c ∪ d ∪ a</code>. I'd like to be able to automatically reassociate and commutate things so that the two <code>a</code>s end up next to each other, so that I can then use <code>a ∪ a = a</code>. Is there a way to use <code>simp</code>, <code>union_comm</code>, and <code>union_assoc</code> to do this kind of sorting? I don't care what the order of the terms is, as long as there is some reasonable total order.</p>",
        "id": 518291609,
        "sender_full_name": "Geoffrey Irving",
        "timestamp": 1747312850
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You'll need a simproc here I think</p>",
        "id": 518292124,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1747312998
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Where you check if <code>Expr.lt</code> says one is ordered before the other, and apply the <code>comm</code> lemma otherwise</p>",
        "id": 518292263,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1747313041
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You can use <code>ac_nf</code> for this assuming your operations implement the associativity and commutativity typeclaaa</p>",
        "id": 518295151,
        "sender_full_name": "Henrik Böving",
        "timestamp": 1747313814
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh, neat! <code>ac_nf</code> is great. And then <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=union_right_idem#doc\">docs#union_right_idem</a> can finish things off.</p>",
        "id": 518296943,
        "sender_full_name": "Geoffrey Irving",
        "timestamp": 1747314228
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh it should do that itself using <code>Std.IdempotentOp</code> but it seems like that instance is missing...</p>",
